Cleaned Transcript:

Speaker 1:
My dear brothers and sisters, we meet as we mourn the death of our beloved President Russell M. Nelson. I speak to you as the President of the Quorum of the Twelve, a position in which I have been sustained in each of our ward, stake, and general conferences for the past seven and a half years. We now go forward with this semiannual general conference, proceeding as planned, with speakers and music assigned by President Nelson after months of preparation. The only additions are my introductory explanation and my speaking in place of President Nelson in the closing session on Sunday afternoon.

This is the first time in about 75 years that a church president has died a few days before a general conference. That has called for us to plan how we could hold the vital leadership meetings in connection with general conference as well as this general session of conference, while also scheduling his funeral as soon as possible. President Nelson understood the value of general conference to provide direction to the saints in the coming months. We honor him by following the planned conference schedule he approved.

In this time of grief we have already held a meeting to pay tribute to President Russell M. Nelson before our general conference meetings and then scheduled his funeral as soon as possible after conference. All of this has been done with the approval of the family of President Nelson and the Quorum of the Twelve.

Since all of us who have been assigned to speak in general conference would like to devote our assigned time to paying a personal tribute to President Nelson, we have therefore asked that all of our conference speakers hold any such tributes to a minimum, deferring elaborate tributes for the funeral which we have already begun to plan.

My own brief tribute, suitable to this conference and to the tributes we have already paid, is this: I love Russell M. Nelson, and I have learned more about the gospel and gospel leadership from my long friendship and association with him than from any other leader I have personally known. He is our model as a servant and follower of the Lord Jesus Christ. Of these things I testify, in the name of Jesus Christ, amen.

Concise Summary:

Key points:
- President Russell M. Nelson has died shortly before the semiannual general conference.
- The speaker is the President of the Quorum of the Twelve and has been sustained in that position for about seven and a half years.
- The conference will proceed as planned using the speakers and music assignments President Nelson approved; only changes are the speaker’s introductory remarks and that he will speak in the closing session in place of President Nelson.
- This is the first time in about 75 years a church president has died just days before a general conference, requiring special planning for leadership meetings and the funeral.
- The funeral has been scheduled as soon as possible after conference, with the approval of President Nelson’s family and the Quorum of the Twelve.
- Conference speakers were asked to keep personal tributes brief and defer elaborate tributes to the funeral.
- The speaker offered a brief personal tribute and testimony about President Nelson’s gospel leadership.

Action items:
- Proceed with the semiannual general conference as scheduled.
- Hold leadership meetings in connection with the conference while accommodating funeral planning.
- Conduct only brief, minimal tributes during conference sessions; reserve longer tributes for the funeral.
- Conduct the funeral as soon as possible after the conference, with family and Quorum approval.

Decisions:
- Follow the planned conference schedule that President Nelson approved.
- Schedule the funeral immediately after conference and coordinate with the family and Quorum of the Twelve.
- Limit in-conference tributes and defer extended tributes to the funeral.

Low-confidence sections/notes:
- Original transcription contained the phrase “President Russell and Nelson,” which is clearly a transcription error. I corrected this to “President Russell M. Nelson” throughout. Confidence: low for that specific original fragment, but high in the corrected reading.
- Timing reference “about 75 years” and the duration “seven and a half years” are taken as stated in the raw transcription; I have not independently verified historical accuracy. Confidence: medium for these numeric details.

